<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP ALBUM CHART; GOOD HEAVENS! A 'SIGN' DISCO IS BACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Is "The Sign" a sign of the times--that disco is rising from the grave? That's 
what disco die-hards are saying about Ace of Base's danceable album, which 
climbed from No. 9 to No. 3 on the pop chart. Some fans are buying it for the 
title song, which danced to the top of the pop singles chart. The Swedish 
group's album also includes its smash single from half a year ago, "All That 
She Wants," which is still selling (No. 24 on the pop singles chart). R. Kelly, 
who specializes in steamy songs, is bumping and grinding his way to the top of 
the charts. His "Bump 'n' Grind" single is No. 6 on the pop chart and his 
album, "12 Play," is No. 2. Tom Petty's "Greatest Hits" continues to be a 
strong seller (No. 9), thanks to a hit single "Mary Jane's Last Dance." Crash 
Test Dummies' "God Shuffled His Feet" jumped from No. 32 to No. 21 and seems 
destined for the Top 10. 
</P>
<P>
 * The soundtrack from the Winona Ryder movie is bounding up the chart, this 
week leaping from No. 57 to No. 17. The Knack's old "My Sharona" is one of the 
album's big songs, as well as Big Mountain's remake of Peter Frampton's "Baby, 
I Love Your Way." The soundtrack also features songs by U2, World Party and 
Dinosaur Jr. 
</P>
<P>
