<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THREE STRIKES: The state Senate has approved a version of the "three strikes 
and you're out" bill aimed at imprisoning repeat offenders (A1). . . . The bill 
proposes mandatory life sentences for third-time felons who have committed two 
prior serious crimes. It goes next to Gov. Pete Wilson, who has said he will 
sign it. . . . Some prosecutors, including Ventura County Dist. Atty. Michael 
D. Bradbury, prefer a different bill that does not count juvenile convictions. 
The Senate-approved bill "has some potential flaws," Bradbury said. "But it's 
certainly better than nothing." 
</P>
<P>
 DETAILS, DETAILS: Carpentry students from Newbury Park High School have been 
hammering away on a replica of the first school in the area (B4). . . . They're 
just about done with the one-room remake of Timber School. To make sure that 
they have it right, they asked former student Margaret Bartel, now 78, to take 
a look. Good thing they did. . . . Bartel, who graduated in the 1920s, 
suggested a change: a wall dividing the cloakroom into boy-girl sections. "I'm 
pretty sure that's the way it was," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 GAME PLAN: Buena High School senior Michelle Giordano will lead the Bulldogs 
tonight when the team takes on Mater Dei in the Southern Section Division I-A 
final at Ventura College (C8). . . . Last year, Giordano sank the winning free 
throws at the buzzer in the division championship against Thousand Oaks. She's 
up for the challenge again. . . . "I love big games like this," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 ON A CURVE: In a new design trend, cars, furniture and other items that once 
were boxy now are curved (E1). . . . Rounded corners grace everything from 
boomboxes to TV remote controls. But not everyone is going for the look. . . . 
"Rectilinear shapes are still very strong in architecture," said Catherine 
Wilson, president of the Ventura County chapter of the American Institute of 
Architects. "Trendiness tends not to be as popular with forms of design that 
will be in the community for years to come." 
</P>
</TEXT>
