<HEADLINE>
<P>
VINCENT PROPOSAL BLASTS BASEBALL HIERARCHY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Former baseball commissioner Fay Vincent assails several owners and a former 
league president in a proposal for a book he plans to write. 
</P>
<P>
 Excepts from the proposal for "And the Horse They Rode In On: My Tumultuous 
Years as Baseball Commissioner," were published in today's editions of the New 
York Times. 
</P>
<P>
 Vincent, who was forced to resign in 1992, makes the following comments, his 
strongest remarks on baseball's hierarchy: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Bill White, the former National League president: a "good man" but 
"incompetent." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Bud Selig, the acting commissioner and Milwaukee Brewer owner: a 
"small-town schlepper" who is the "emblem of baseball's decline." 
</P>
<P>
 -- New York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner: "the most hated man in 
baseball." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Chicago White Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf: "dangerous" and more to blame for 
the "poor state of baseball than anyone else." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Dodger owner Peter O'Malley: a "nitwit" and "bigot." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Cincinnati Red owner Marge Schott: the owner who "does the dumbest things." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Jackie Autry, the Angels' executive vice president and wife of owner Gene 
Autry: "mean-spirited and not bright." 
</P>
<P>
 Vincent said he "wouldn't put much stock in the tone" of the proposal, 
contending it was not in keeping with his style. When informed the excerpts 
would be published in the newspaper, he told the Times he would no longer write 
the book. 
</P>
<P>
 The Times said the 40-page proposal is being shopped to publishing houses by 
the William Morris Agency. After publishing rights are auctioned, the book 
would be written by Vincent and David Kaplan of Newsweek. 
</P>
</TEXT>
